{# Human task: user reviews and (optionally) edits the change
   plan. Same shape as create's design-review gate. #}
# Review the update plan

The `design-author-update` agent has produced a structured
change plan at:

`{{ upstream['design-author-update'].task_path }}` (canonical edit target)

The `design-render-update` tool has rendered it as a
human-readable markdown report at:

`{{ upstream['design-render-update'].output.report_path }}`

## Driving the gate

1. Open the rendered markdown in the editor for the user
   (use the `editor` skill: `editor.sh show file <path>`).
   Show the markdown — it is far easier to scan than the
   raw YAML.
2. STOP and wait for the user. The user can:
   - **Accept** — the plan is good; proceed to
     `modify-changes`.
   - **Revise** — request changes. Capture their feedback
     verbatim. The gate latches back to
     `design-author-update`, which re-runs and reads the
     feedback to produce a new plan; the gate then
     re-presents it. Iterate until accept.
   - **Decline** — major rework needed, abandon the run.
     Report BLOCKED.

## Output

The `design-review-update` output matches
`schemas/design-author-update.yaml` (the same shape as the
`design-author-update` agent) plus a `decision` field:

- **Accept:** copy the (possibly hand-tweaked) change plan
  YAML to `{{ task.output_path }}` and set
  `decision: accept`. Leave `revise_reason` unset.
- **Revise:** copy the current change plan YAML to
  `{{ task.output_path }}`, set `decision: revise`, and set
  `revise_reason` to the user's feedback (free text). The
  `while` latch (`decision == 'revise'`) loops back to
  `design-author-update`, which reads `revise_reason` and
  regenerates.
- **Decline:** report BLOCKED and stop the workflow.

`decision` and `revise_reason` are optional in the schema (the
`design-author-update` agent omits them); the gate always
sets `decision`. The `modify-changes` agent reads
`design-review-update.output.yaml`, NOT the upstream
`design-author-update` output.
